data: Likely the deadliest tornado in recorded world history, this storm destroyed everything but a few trees from Daultipur to Salturia.
The village of Balurchar was completely destroyed, with eight other villages almost totally leveled.
† Wiped seven villages off the map. The death toll may have been as high as 1400, but official records conflict. There were no survivors from the village of Bhabanipur, where around 400people lived.
All buildings and trees in Madaripur and Shibchar were destroyed.
North of Cooch Behar and surrounding area
Spawned by a separate storm from the Dhaka tornado, which killed 660 earlier in the day.
Border of Orissa and West Bengal
† Destroyed several hundred homes in the city, many of good construction. Over 100 people were still in hospitals when this official death toll was published, so the actual death toll may be higher.
† In the same outbreak as the Tupelo tornado, destroyed a large section of downtown at the start of the work day. Forty people were still missing when this death toll was published.
† A fifteen square mile (38km 2 ) area was "wiped clean".
EF5 tornado struck the southern part of the city along a west-to-east path miles (km) wide by miles (km) long, destroying one of two hospitals in the city.
Struck the town just as a circus was ending, likely inflating the death toll.
Destroyed a one mile stretch of houses on Coldwater Road.
Thirty or more were killed in a six-story furniture store when it collapsed, with several others killed in cars by the falling bricks.
Around 100 buildings destroyed. Killed 85 initially, with the rest dying from their injuries later.
Cut a 0.25mile (0.4km) gouge through the city, destroying or damaging almost 2000 homes.

In the past, this was plotted as a record-length 293-mile (472-km) long tornado path, killing 110, but scientists now know that it was a family of at least four tornadoes. A single tornado killed at least 93people in and near these two cities, and 101 deaths is the best modern estimate for a single tornado.
